    <section id="import-auto-idm351533184">
      <title>Introduction </title>
      <section id="import-auto-idm1083627152">
        <title>Infrared spectroscopy </title>
        <para id="import-auto-idm360525264">In infrared (IR) spectroscopy, when light interacts with a complex, several molecular vibrations occur by absorbing light at specific frequencies. The absorbed light frequency depends on the mass of the atoms in the molecule, the bond strength, and the polarity of the bond. Some of the molecular vibrations include: stretching, bending, twisting and rocking. <link target-id="import-auto-idm992607120"/> shows the possible vibration modes of water. In order for a vibration to be IR active, a change in the dipole moment of the molecule must occur. The intensity of absorption bands depends on the extent of change in the dipole moment of the molecule upon light interaction. </para><figure id="import-auto-idm992607120"><media id="import-auto-idm1235029008" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/Picture 3-d44c.png" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
          </media>
        <caption>Vibration modes of water, showing stretching and bending modes. Adapted from R. Silverstein, F. Webester, D. Kiemle and D. Bryce, S<emphasis effect="italics">pectrometric Identification of Organic Compounds</emphasis>, 8<sup>th</sup> ed., John Wiley &amp; Sons, New York (2015).</caption></figure></section>
      <section id="import-auto-idm993622064">
        <title>IR spectroscopy of organometallic compounds </title>
        <para id="import-auto-idm1246027104">IR spectroscopy is a great analytical tool for ligand identification in organometallic complexes, because data collection is fast, and different ligand binding modes have distinct absorption frequencies. <link url="https://cnx.org/contents/uieDnVBC@23.1:6oYLai6Q@1/Fourier-Transform-Infrared-Spe" window="new"> Fourier Transform Infrared Spectroscopy of Metal Ligand Complexes </link> has a list of absorption bands of typical functional groups. When a ligand binds to a metal, the absorption frequency of the ligand changes reflecting the new electronic structure of the complex. Organometallic complexes with different geometry also absorb light at different frequencies. </para></section>
      <section id="import-auto-idm847840672">
        <title>Advantage of IR techniques</title>
        <para id="import-auto-idm1226298608">Infrared (IR) spectroscopy is a good analytical tool for geometry identification of organometallic compounds. It is a fast and relatively simple analytical technique. Moreover, metal-ligand chemistry has been studied extensively via IR spectroscopy and tables of different ligand frequencies have been reported in various studies, which makes it easier to determine the ligand and the complex’s structure based on those studies. </para></section>
    </section>
    <section id="import-auto-idm1067620592">
      <title>IR Spectroscopy instrumentation</title><section id="import-auto-idm315728576">
        <title>Sample preparation </title>
        <para id="import-auto-idm342263088">While the sample preparation procedure was explained in great details in <link url="https://cnx.org/contents/uieDnVBC@23.1:vdl5g77_@1/IR-Sample-Preparation-A-Practi" window="new"> IR Sample Preparation: A Practical Guide</link>, modern Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) instruments have developed rapidly over the past few years especially with instruments with increased sensitivity, resolution and speed. Some modern FT-IR sample cells are made out of diamond crystals that are strong. This kind of cells are versatile and great for testing liquids, powders, and rubbers without requiring any sample preparation. </para></section>
      <section id="import-auto-idm852317808"><title>Spectra interpretation</title><para id="import-auto-idm861419360"><link url="https://cnx.org/contents/uieDnVBC@23.1:6oYLai6Q@1/Fourier-Transform-Infrared-Spe" window="new"> Fourier Transform Infrared Spectroscopy of Metal Ligand Complexes </link> has a great explanation of the common FT-IR bands. Nonetheless, <link target-id="import-auto-idm364911904"/> shows a regional representation of the positions of some typical functional groups. </para><figure id="import-auto-idm364911904"><media id="import-auto-idm854404272" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/Picture 6-d83f.png" width="500" print-width="5in"/></media><caption>Regional assignment of the typical functional groups. </caption></figure></section></section>
    <section id="import-auto-idm341649152">
      <title>Case studies </title>
      <section id="import-auto-idm865636992"><title>Isomers identification </title><section id="eip-831"><title>Coordination isomers</title><para id="import-auto-idm361724992">Geometric isomers can sometimes have different physical properties and applications. Therefore, having good analytical method for identifying isomers is crucial to differentiate between isomers. FTIR is a good tool for isomer identification because different isomers have distinct IR bands. For example, the <emphasis effect="italics">cis</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">trans</emphasis> isomers of PtCl<sub>2</sub>(PEt<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub>, have different ν<sub>Pt-P</sub> and ν<sub>Pt-Cl</sub> stretching as shown in <link target-id="import-auto-idm364911905"/>. The difference in stretching frequency is due to the change in bond length of the <emphasis effect="italics">cis</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">trans</emphasis> isomers, inducing the change in the absorption frequency (<link target-id="eip-780"/>). </para><figure id="import-auto-idm364911905"><media id="import-auto-idm854404276Pt" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/IR_1.jpg" width="300" print-width="3in"/></media><caption>The structure, bond length, and absorption frequency of <emphasis effect="italics">cis</emphasis>- and <emphasis effect="italics">trans</emphasis>-PtCl<sub>2</sub>(PEt<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2.</sub> Adapted from S. Komiya, <emphasis effect="italics">Synthesis of Organometallic Compounds: A Practical Guide</emphasis> , John Wiley Sons , New York (1997).</caption></figure><table id="eip-780" summary="Selected structural and IR parameters for cis and trans isomers.">
