<section id="eip-92"><title>Ligand coordination isomers</title><para id="import-auto-idm1048657073">Linkage ligands can have multiple binding sites to a metals center or multiple metal centers. One example is the nitrite ion (NO<sub>2</sub><sup>-</sup>), which can bind to the metal via the oxygen atom to form a nitrito ligand or via nitrogen atom to form nitro ligand <link target-id="import-auto-idm1038003025"/>. IR spectroscopy can be used to distinguish between linkage ligands. <link target-id="import-auto-idm1076899457"/> has some of the frequencies of the ligands with multiple binding sites.</para><figure id="import-auto-idm1038003025"><media id="import-auto-idm845514577" alt="">
