</section><section id="import-auto-idm1182515232"><title>Metal carbonyl complexes </title><para id="import-auto-idm901758000">A classic example of metal-ligand complexes are metal carbonyl complexes. They are wildly used as catalysis and have been studied extensively in literature. The IR stretching of free isolated CO occurs at 2143 cm<sup>-1</sup>; however, the frequency of ν<sub>C-O</sub> stretching in a complex differs from that of the free CO. The change of the stretching frequency is related to electron density of the metal. Having extra electrons in the system promotes filling π<sup>∗</sup> anti-bonding orbitals weakening the C–O bond and lowering absorption frequency. <link target-id="import-auto-idm996253536"/> shows how the charge of the complex affects the C-O stretching frequency on increasing the charge, while maintaining the overall electron configuration, i.e., d<sup>18</sup>. </para><table id="import-auto-idm996253536" summary="C-O stretching of carbonyl complexes with different charges.">
