</table><para id="import-auto-idm315142368">Furthermore, a single metal atom can bind to multiple carbonyl molecules to form complexes with different geometries depending on the number of carbonyl groups in the formed complex. <link target-id="import-auto-idm846269840"/> shows how changing the number of CO ligands around Mn changes the overall symmetry of the molecule, which changes the number of the IR active bands and the absorption frequency. To measure the CO stretching of different manganese carbonyl cations, [Mn(CO)<sub>6</sub>]<sup>+</sup> was bombarded with argon molecules to fragment the complex giving a mixture of [Mn(CO)<sub>n</sub>]<sup>+</sup>(Ar)<sub>m</sub> complexes, from which argon is eliminated to measure the IR spectrum of the [Mn(CO)<sub>n</sub>]<sup>+</sup> species.  <link target-id="import-auto-idm1020392608"/> shows the IR spectra of [Mn(CO)<sub>n</sub>]<sup>+</sup>(Ar)<sub>m</sub> complexes after argon elimination. </para><table id="import-auto-idm846269840" summary="Symmetry elements of the different Mn carbonyl complexes. The bold symmetry element indicates the most stable structure of the complex.">
