        <title>Ruthenium impregnated zeolite geometry identification </title>
        <para id="import-auto-idm870284768">Zeolites are porous materials that are widely used in industry as catalysis. The active catalytic site on zeolites is a metal oxide complex. The activity of the catalyst is determined based on the geometry of the metal oxide. For example, rhenium on zeolites can exhibit both tetrahedral and octahedral geometry having IR signals at 912 and 924 cm<sup>-1</sup>, respectively. The tetrahedral geometry is under coordinated, making the tetrahedral rhenium site highly active with catalytic properties. </para>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section id="import-auto-idm991129040">
      <title>Limitations </title>
      <para id="import-auto-idm349893904">While IR spectroscopy is considered a powerful tool for organometallics characterization, it has some disadvantages and limitations. For example, the sample preparation can be laborious depending on the available IR cell. KBr ballets requires some skills and the nujol mulls can sometimes be tedious. Furthermore, their IR bands can potentially overlap hiding some important, but weak, bands. </para>
    </section>
